[normal]Written evidence from [bold]Greater Manchester Combined Authority[bold] and Transport for Greater Manchester (LTD0024)[bold]Greater Manch
[normal]ester Combined Authority (GMCA)
[normal] has welcomed the Government’s policy to devolve resources, decision-making and functions away from Whitehall and toward the city region.
[normal] This submission
[normal] to the Committee
[normal] highlights in particular:
[normal]1.[bold]              [bold]W[bold]hat is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local level [bold]decision-making on transport expenditure? What are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government’s approach? Are there better models?[bold] 
[normal]1.1
[normal]              
[normal]Greater Manchester established the
[normal] first Combined Authority in t
[normal]he country
[normal] 
[normal]in April 2011, reflecting the importa
[normal]nce given to governance at the heart of our city region growth strategy, alongside the GMLEP, building on the long-standing
[normal] tradition of effective joint working 
[normal]across local public and private sector partners in the city region. 
[normal]1.2
[normal]              
[normal]We share Government’s 
[normal]view that an over-centralised state can act as a barrier to the most effective
[normal] local
[normal] public sector reform and economic growth
[normal]; and w
[normal]e 
[normal]have developed
[normal] a compelling case for how devolution
[normal] can
[normal] yield significant benefits
[normal] at both the local and national level
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]De
[normal]volution
[normal] to the right level of local government enables effective coordination and prioritisation of spending to be maintained in support of local growth and regeneration objectives. 
[normal]Moreo
[normal]ver, a
[normal]t a time when public resources are scarce,
[normal] we believe
[normal] that
[normal] i
[normal]t is more important than ever that we allow places with mature governance arrangements and clear strategies to determine their own transport priorities to drive GVA and growth.
[normal]1.
[normal]3
[normal]              
[normal]City region governance in Greater Manchester mirrors the conurbation’s func
[normal]tional economic area
[normal] 
[normal]that generates an annual GVA of £48 billion
[normal] and is 
[normal]home to
[normal] a growing population of over 2.7 million people. 
[normal]Devolution has enabled decisions and funding considerations in relation to transport to be
[normal] 
[normal]made in a much broader context,
[normal] including strategic planning, future housing and employment site development, 
[normal]town centre regeneration -
[normal] and provides for a fuller understanding of environmental impacts. 
[normal]1.4
[normal]              
[normal]This has enabled
[normal] GMCA and the GM Local Enterprise Partnership 
[normal]to secure
[normal] a long 
[normal]term consensus 
[normal]on policy direction and spending priorities, as set out in 
[normal]the
[normal] recently revised
[normal] G
[normal]reater 
[normal]M
[normal]anchester
[normal] Strategy, 
[normal]Stronger Together
[normal], with a clear focus on growth and value for money. 
[normal]Critically
[normal], through the GVA-led investment criteria that we hav
[normal]e developed and adopted locally, we are able to ensure that our investment priorities are consistently focussed on growth in a way that Government department appraisal 
[normal]approaches cannot, with
[normal] this
[normal] being
[normal] particularly so in the case of 
[normal]DfT
[normal]’s
[normal] transport apprai
[normal]sal methodologies
[normal].  
[normal]2.[bold]              [bold]Do local bodies (including local authorities, local enterprise partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport authorities and local transport boards) have the capacity to assess, prioritise and deliver local [bold]transport schemes? What would the optimum delivery body look like?[bold]2.1
[normal]              
[normal]Our
[normal] city region governance system is supported by t
[normal]he transport expertise developed by Transport for Greater Manchester (
[normal]TfGM
[normal], the renamed GM Passeng
[normal]er Transport Executive) providing
[normal] 
[normal]po
[normal]licy support, technical appraisal and the delivery capability required for transport schem
[normal]es of all sizes and complexity. 
[normal]This evolving, adaptable 
[normal]and
[normal] a
[normal]ccountable governance structure has 
[normal]ensured that Greater Manchester is well placed to
[normal] work with Governme
[normal]nt’s
[normal] new approach to funding major transport schemes
[normal] to maximise local and national policy objectives
[normal].
[normal] We look forward to developing further aspects of devolution through the new Growth Deal that we intend to agree with Government in 2014 with a view to pr
[normal]ogressing reform and 
[normal]efficiency across all agencies involved in delivering transport investment and services in Greater Manchester
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal] 
[normal]2.2
[normal]              
[normal]T
[normal]he o
[normal]ptimum delivery body
[normal] depend
[normal]s
[normal] on local circumstances
[normal] and requirements
[normal]; 
[normal]it is to some extent 
[normal]a corollary of the devolutionary process that different arrangements will emerge as appropriate responses for 
[normal]different
[normal] geographies and circumstances. 
[normal]Therefore, we welcome the Government
[normal]’s
[normal] continued
[normal] policy
[normal] intention, as established under the recent City D
[normal]eal policy, to establish local arrangements for devolution that reflect local governance arrangements and local priorities in different parts of the country
[normal], so that those who are ready to progress with devolution quickly are able to do so
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]This is importa
[normal]nt in the case of Greater Manchester, where we have strong governance and delivery capacity already in place, thanks to the £2 billion transport investment programme underway here, and are therefore ready to accelerate the rate of devolution to a greater d
[normal]egree than will be the case elsewhere. 
