[normal]3.[bold]              [bold]What is the best way of dealing with major transport schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Greater Manchester maintains a dialogue with neighbouring authorities, 
[normal]with a view to 
[normal]addressing
[normal] connectivity
[normal] barriers that if
[normal] resolved collaboratively can yield benefits for the wider economic area.
[normal] 
[normal]This contemporary form of engagement offers
[normal] significant
[normal] benefits over the previous regional
[normal] model, which attempted to determine
[normal] 
[normal]collaboration
[normal] between local authorities on the basis of artificial boundaries such as the North West. In the absence of these structural constraints, Greater Manchester has established new cross-boundary working, with South and West Yorkshire for example,
[normal] that better reflect economic interdependencies and opportunities to secure improvements through economies of scale.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3
[normal].3
[normal]              
[normal]We see further scope for collaboration in the future, particularly if the providers of key motorway and rail infrastructure linking 
[normal]Greater Manchester with neighbouring areas are also drawn into close working arrangements with us. However, under current arrangements that limit the funding available to local transport, neighbouring authorities are often constrained in their ability to c
[normal]ollaborate in direct spending partnerships. Long-term funding deals with authorities would provide greater scope for cross-
[normal]boundary spending partnerships.
[normal]4[bold].[bold]              [bold]How effectively do local bodies work with each other and with Government departments and national [bold]transport agencies?[bold]              
[normal]4
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]In recent years, northern transport authorities have demonstrated their ability to collectively prioritise and promote 
[normal]genuinely transformative transport schemes that deliver cross-boundary impacts
[normal]. 
[normal]The 
[normal]Northern Hub
[normal] rail investmen
[normal]t programme was established as a national investment priority following a concerted effort
[normal] by all northern partners
[normal] 
[normal]and Network Rail 
[normal]to promote a clear and consistent business case for the expansion of rail capacity to secure regional benefits
[normal]. 
[normal]Closer 
[normal]working between 
[normal]TfGM
[normal], Greater Manchester highway authorities
[normal] and the Highways Agency has also begun to bring benefits 
[normal]through a series of protocols that establish common principles for working across adjacent parts of the strategic and local highway system
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Further effective
[normal] project-based
[normal] joint working 
[normal]has also taken place 
[normal]in relation to a number of schemes, such as the construction of the 
[normal]Ordsall
[normal] Chord (a key element of the Northern Hub), a complex scheme which involves local highways
[normal] and planning authorit
[normal]ies, Highways Agency, Network Rail and
[normal] 
[normal]TfGM
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4
[normal].2
[normal]              
[normal]This local approach to regular and effective
[normal] working 
[normal]is
[normal] increasingly
[normal] mirrored at a
[normal] planning and governance
[normal] level, with regular dialogue 
[normal]now in place
[normal] between 
[normal]TfGM
[normal], the Highways Agency, Network Rail
[normal] and 
[normal]DfT
[normal] 
[normal]t
[normal]hrough a series of officer 
[normal]engagement channels
[normal].  In addition, representatives of Network Rail and other agencies attend meetings of the Transport for Greater Manchester Committee, both to brief members on specific infrastructure developments and to respond
[normal] to service issues.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4
[normal].3
[normal]              
[normal]We see scope to take these relationships further to ensure consistent alignment
[normal] between local economic priorities and 
[normal]investment decisions made by national bodies,
[normal] such as Network Rail and the Highways Agency.
[normal] 
[normal]We are keen, for 
[normal]example, to explore the opportunities offered by the forthcoming revised Highways Agency arrangements to align investment activities across the local and strategic highways system in Greater Manchester.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]              
[normal]In the context of rail
[normal] devolution
[normal] and preparatio
[normal]n for HS2
[normal],
[normal] we 
[normal]are proposing 
[normal]a 
[normal]re
[normal]fresh
[normal]ed
[normal] relationship 
[normal]with
[normal] Network Rail
[normal] to ensure that national investment supports local growth priorities and to promote partnership spending arrangements
[normal].
[normal] Critically,
[normal] 
[normal]HS2 offers a unique opportunity to secure long-term gro
[normal]wth and regeneration in Greater Manchester, subject to the right levels of facility being secured at Manchester Piccadilly in particular. This will require long-term partnership funding arrangements with Network Rail that enable optimal scheduling of inves
[normal]tment across Control Periods 5, 6 and 7 to ensure that transformational facilities can be delivered to unlock regeneration benefits at the earliest opportunity.
[normal]5[bold].[bold]              [bold]Do the current funding streams for major local transport schemes meet the needs of local [bold]authorities? How do current funding streams compare with previous arrangements?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]Effective devolution requires
[normal] a predictable and stable funding regime over the long term
[normal]. 
[normal]T
[normal]he 
[normal]level of funding available for major local transport schemes
[normal] 
[normal]has 
[normal]historically
[normal] 
[normal]been
[normal] significantly
[normal] below 
[normal]that required to meet economic growth potential. 
[normal]T
[normal]here remains a substantial funding gap between the large city regions outside London and the capital itself, with Treasury figures showing that the total public spend per head on t
[normal]ransport in London is 2.3 times greater than the spend per head for the North of England and the West Midlands combined (source: 
[normal]pteg
[normal]).
[normal] In addition
[normal], the process for determining major scheme funding decisions has been constrained by a scheme-by-scheme analy
[normal]sis by central government. Collectively, this has undermined the ability of authorities to promote the programmes of infrastructure investment that give wealth creators the confidence to undertake entrepreneurial investment in a local economy, as has been 
[normal]seen in London from the Docklands Light Railway onwards. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5
[normal].2
[normal]              
[normal]L
[normal]ocally, the Association of Greater Manchester Authorities
[normal] 
[normal]sought to address this through 
[normal]the £1.5 billion GM Transport Fund (GMTF)
[normal] in 2009. This
[normal] initiative built on the “self-help” approach to transport infrastructure provision that Greater 
[normal]Manchester adopted two years’ earlier to unlock a funding package for the £575 million 
[normal]Metrolink
[normal] Phase 3(a) programme, more than half of which 
[normal]was
[normal] provided by 
[normal]local funding. GMTF 
[normal]supports the delivery 
[normal]of economically focused transport investment 
[normal]through long-term commitments made both locally and for 
[normal]central government major scheme funding
[normal] 
[normal]as
[normal] set out below
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Funding Source[bold]Capital Buying Power (£ m)[bold]Share of to[bold]tal[bold]DfT
[normal] Major Scheme Funding
