[normal]              
[normal]H
[normal]ence, major scheme transport funding in Greater Manchester is now a complex product of direct (major schemes) and indirect (top-sliced ITB) central government funding alongside local prudential borrowing. 
[normal]T
[normal]hrough the
[normal] 2012
[normal] City Deal
[normal], GMCA has agreed the principle of an
[normal] 
[normal]“
[normal]Earn Back
[normal]”
[normal] model
[normal] with Government, which
[normal] builds on the self-sufficiency 
[normal]approach to
[normal] delivering infrastructure investment. The model uses a formula to provide a
[normal] long-term
[normal] revenue stream to
[normal] support further long
[normal]-term investment, subject to
[normal] additional GVA, 
[normal]measured i
[normal]n changes in rateable values
[normal] at the Greater Manchester level,
[normal] being
[normal] created relative to a 2015 baseline. Earn Back, therefore, provides
[normal] both a future revenue stream and
[normal] an additional incentive for Grea
[normal]ter Manchester to prioritise local government spending to maximise GVA growth.
[normal] 
[normal]More recently, a number of other city regions have indicated their intention to develop self-reliance models as part of moves towards revised governance, demonstrating the impor
[normal]tance of this approach. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4
[normal]              
[normal]However, these new approaches will require consistent long-term commitment from all transport funding partners if their impact is to be sustained over the long-term. For example, through the forthcoming Local Growth Fund arran
[normal]gement, Greater Manchester has been allocated a core provision of £110 million from 2015/16 to 2020/21, extending to £199 million by 2024/25. Whilst it is welcome to see Government establishing longer-term core allocations of major sche
[normal]me funding, the scal
[normal]e of funding should be viewed alongside spending priorities for the city region. 
[normal] 
[normal]For the period to the end of the current decade alone, the Greater Manchester LTB has identified a minimum investment pip
[normal]eline of more than £300 million
[normal] schemes,
[normal] 
[normal]alongside the £350 million 
[normal]Metrolink
[normal] extension to Trafford Park 
[normal]to support
[normal] growth in the country’s largest industrial park, which is also home to the Trafford Centre and adjacent to the nationally important M60/M62 motorway. Beyond this, 
[normal]GMCA has
[normal] set out t
[normal]he case for a major programme of tram-train developments, combining the country’s largest tram system with one of the fastest growing urban rail markets to enable growth to be sustained into the 2020s
[normal], alongside the delivery of transformational HS2 facilit
[normal]ies discussed at 4.4 above
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5
[normal].6
[normal]              
[normal]T
[normal]he Committee is
[normal] also
[normal] encouraged to not overlook the importance of
[normal] ITB
[normal] funding, which enables
[normal] local 
[normal]transport authorities to directly deliver smaller investment schemes, such as
[normal] local access
[normal] and highways pinch-point
[normal] measures
[normal], 
[normal]and acts as a long-term
[normal] funding source to
[normal] secure optimal larger solutions that could not be supported through development contributions alone
[normal]. 
[normal]Since the CSR in 2010, ITB funding has reduced by 
[normal]around 50% compared to levels
[normal] under the LTP2 period 
[normal]to 
[normal]2010/11
[normal]. 
[normal]We welcome the fact that ITB has been maintained as a p
[normal]olicy for 2015/16 onwards, 
[normal]but note
[normal] that the £458 million per annum to be made available for ITB nationally
[normal] will still be around 30% lower than the national provision in 2010/11. 
[normal]In additio
[normal]n
