[normal]TfGM
[normal]. However, this has proved
[normal] increasingly challenging for local authorities elsewhere
[normal] and risks doing so here too in th
[normal]e context of further reductions in local authority funding
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5
[normal].8
[normal]              
[normal]Finally,
[normal] we would highlight 
[normal]the 
[normal]wider
[normal] implications of further reductions in the local authority revenue support grant, 
[normal]following
[normal] the
[normal] recent Spending Round
[normal]. 
[normal]Consistent a
[normal]ccess to revenue funds 
[normal]for 
[normal]on-going travel services and promotion measures
[normal], which
[normal] 
[normal]are 
[normal]essential in sustaining modal shift amongst commuters,
[normal] 
[normal]has been a long-standing 
[normal]issue
[normal].
[normal] R
[normal]educed local authority revenues have already brought reductions in local supported
[normal] bus services and other travel support measures in many areas of the country
[normal];
[normal] and
[normal] they
[normal] are likely to place increasing downward pressure on budgets for transport services in the major city regions outside London. The element of revenue funding provided thro
[normal]ugh the Local Sustainable Transport Fund (LSTF) has been a welcome change in this regard, 
[normal]albeit that LSTF is still time-limited in nature even after t
[normal]he recent commitment to its extension
[normal] for 2015/16. The recent national LSTF conference highlighted the ch
[normal]allenges that this will bring beyond 2015/16 for authorities in sustaining support for local carbon and active travel measures. 
[normal]6[bold].[bold]              [bold]What impact will the devolution in 2015 of funding to Local Transport Bodies and the introduction of the Single Local Growth[bold] Fund have?[bold]6
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]As already set out above, Greater Manchester is well-prepared for the further devolution and changes to transport spending governance that the LGF will bring.
[normal] Our governance arrangements remain the subject of on-going review, and we 
[normal]welcome
[normal] the opportunity through a future Growth Deal to establish local arrangements across the entire Greater Manchester investment framework, which 
[normal]may remove the need for an explicit LTB. 
[normal] We will
[normal] also be 
[normal]be
[normal] looking to utilise this
[normal] opportunity to secure furthe
[normal]r parallel reforms that ensure that the impact of LGF funds can be best maximised through clear long-term partnership and programme based investment frameworks across all local transport agencies operating in the city region. 
[normal]7[bold].[bold]              [bold]How can local authorities [bold]attract greater investment from the private sector for the delivery and maintenance of local transport infrastructure? What scope is there for the use of alternative funding streams?[bold]7
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]As set out under question 5
[normal] above, a core long-term central governmen
[normal]t funding commitment to local transport funding is a key component in attracting private sector funding. As also set out earlier, the Greater Manchester authorities recognise that not all of this funding can be accessed through traditional major schemes fu
[normal]nding channels, but rather requires all parts of the public sector to align spending programmes in the interests of consistency. This could potentially include greater use of European Structural Investment Funds
[normal] if UK Government can be persuaded of the cas
[normal]e to press for greater deployment of EU SI Funds to support transport schemes that unlock real low carbon economic opportunity.
[normal] 
[normal]7
[normal].2
[normal]              
[normal]It also requires innovative thinking on the relationship between transport spending and future ret
[normal]urns to the Treasury as 
[normal]shown in principle by the
[normal] Earn Back model and in the current example of the funding agreement established for the transport infrastructure needed to support the Battersea/Nine Elms development in London. Looking towards the delivery of HS2 facilities, such
[normal] as the proposed stations in Manchester, we see a need to develop this innovative approach to finance further
[normal], alongside the need for a long-term rail funding regime discussed 
[normal]above,
[normal] so as to ensure that transport facilities are delivered at a scale and pa
[normal]ce that ensures the wider economic impact of transport investment – in the form of new local employment and regeneration – is fully realised in practice.
[normal]8[bold].[bold]              [bold]How clear are the lines of accountability for local decision making on transport expenditure?[bold]8
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]A
[normal]s set out above, 
[normal]G
[normal]reater Manchester has established clear lines of accountability and a robust governance framework 
[normal]for transport expenditure decision making
[normal]. However, there remains some uncertainty over the specific role that 
[normal]DfT
[normal] will play in supporting 
[normal]devolved delivery of transport investment from April 2015. We would welcome clarity on this at the earliest opportunity
[normal], so as
[normal] to ensure that systems can be best develop
[normal]ed to support shared objectives.
